    {
      "id": "3a0eb1da3c9f3088a6b85a223bedbc415eed55dc",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 302,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "paf@cray.com",
        "username": "paf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2018-11-19 20:26:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1\n\nUgh.  I dislike that it looks like (in llite_lib) we implement truncate_inode_pages_final.  We do not.\n\nOlder kernels that don't have truncate_inode_pages_final [CentOS 6, so not involved here] just use truncate_inode_pages.  truncate_inode_pages_final is a much more complicated function added to support a new feature.\n\nI guess it bothers me because providing a function suggests we implement that function, as opposed to something like:\n#define truncate_inode_pages_final truncate_inode_pages\n\nWhich makes clearer that there's just a mapping.\n\nBut the generated code is the same, and it's all old news anyway.  (Though related - Moving to newer kernels meant the workaround had to be moved out of that #ifdef'ed code, hence this patch.)\n\nAnd this patch itself looks correct to me.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
